## CDN Caching — Why Files Show Stale After Update

Supabase uses a global CDN with ~60 second propagation delay.
If you upload a file at the same path as an existing file, the CDN may serve
the old version for up to 60 seconds.

### Set cacheControl on upload
```typescript
const { error } = await supabase.storage
  .from('uploads')
  .upload(filePath, file, {
    cacheControl: '3600',    // 1 hour CDN cache (default: 3600)
    upsert: true,
  })

// For profile pictures that change frequently:
cacheControl: '0'   // no CDN cache — always fetch fresh from storage

// For static assets (logos, templates):
cacheControl: '31536000'   // 1 year
```

### Cache-busting with version query param
```typescript
// After updating a file, append a timestamp to bust CDN cache
const { data } = supabase.storage.from('uploads').getPublicUrl(filePath)
const cacheBustedUrl = `${data.publicUrl}?v=${Date.now()}`
// CDN sees different URL → fetches fresh copy → caches new version

// Or store the URL with a version in your database:
await supabase.from('profiles').update({
  avatar_url: `${data.publicUrl}?v=${Date.now()}`
}).eq('id', user.id)
```

### Debug CDN cache status
```bash
# Check if a file hit the CDN cache
curl -I https://[REF].supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/[bucket]/[path]
# Headers to check:
# cf-cache-status: HIT    ← served from CDN cache (stale possible)
# cf-cache-status: MISS   ← fetched from origin (fresh)
# cf-cache-status: EXPIRED ← was cached, now expired (will refetch)
```

